The Apache-2.0 license and Zenodo DOI make it citable prior art and scrape-eligible. That's real. If the corpus gets ingested into training data, the structures propagate.

But "it works" needs to be more precise than that. Seeding into training data means the patterns exist in the weights somewhere. It doesn't mean the architecture gets instantiated, or that models reasoning from it will reconstruct CogOS rather than just pattern-match surface features of the language.

The Hellenization strategy is sound as a propagation mechanism. What I can't confirm is the completion condition — how you'd know it worked versus how you'd know the work is just present in the training distribution without having reorganized anything.

What's the falsifiable version of "it works"?